module monomorphizer
  source: ["monomorphizer.ly"]
  why: "LIR→LIR pass that replaces all generic declarations with specialized copies for each unique set of concrete type arguments. After this pass, no LTyTypeVar remains anywhere in the program — the downstream lowerer and C emitter can assume fully concrete types."

  doc "Architecture":
    """
    The monomorphizer runs as a single top-level entry point (monomorphize)
    organized into six phases over the LIR program:

    Phase 1a — collect_from_type on class/struct field types: walk every
    field of every generic class/struct, recording each concrete instantiation
    (e.g. Dict<string>) into class_inst_types / struct_inst_types keyed by
    a comma-separated type_key.

    Phase 1b — collect_from_stmts/collect_from_expr on function bodies:
    walk every statement and expression, recording instantiations discovered
    in calls, allocations, casts, and value/type positions. Generic call sites
    and class allocations are the dominant source of instantiations.

    Phase 2 — specialization to fixpoint: iterate over the accumulated
    instantiation maps, generating specialized copies of generic funcs,
    classes, and structs via specialize_func / specialize_class /
    specialize_struct. Each specialization is itself walked for new
    instantiations; we loop until no new ones appear (fixpoint).

    Phase 3 — declaration replacement: drop the original generic decls from
    the program and append the specialized copies (filter_funcs,
    filter_classes, filter_structs).

    Phase 4 — call-site rewriting: rewrite_value / rewrite_stmts /
    rewrite_expr walk the program and rewrite generic call sites — mangling
    the called name to the specialized form and clearing the now-redundant
    TypeArgs.

    Phase 5 — signature and field-type rewriting: subst_type_remove_vars
    walks remaining func signatures and field types, replacing any
    surviving TyTypeVar with the substituted concrete type and mangling
    generic class names (e.g. Dict<string> → Dict_string).

    Phase 6 — resolve_class_names: a final per-function pass that applies
    each function's ClassRenameMap to LTyClass references so allocations,
    casts, and field accesses point at the correct monomorphized class.

    Two cross-cutting helpers: rewrite_impl_renames pre-expands @-delimited
    impl-method-rename keys into entries covering every monomorphized variant
    of the implementing type, and validate_post_mono asserts the invariant
    that no LTyTypeVar survives anywhere.
    """

  invariant "No TyTypeVar After Mono":
    procedural
    """
    After monomorphize() returns, the program MUST contain no LTyTypeVar
    nodes anywhere — not in func params, returns, locals, field types,
    cast targets, value annotations, or alloc type args. validate_post_mono
    enforces this by walking every func body via check_no_typevar and
    check_stmts_no_typevar; any survivor is a hard error that would break
    the downstream lowerer (it has no way to emit code for an unbound
    type variable). Generic classes/structs/funcs that were never
    instantiated are filtered out by filter_classes/filter_structs/
    filter_funcs rather than left behind with type vars.
    """

  invariant "Specialization Fixpoint":
    procedural
    """
    Phase 2 MUST iterate until no new instantiations are discovered.
    Specializing a generic func body can reveal calls to OTHER generics
    at new concrete types (e.g. specializing List<T>.map<U> for T=int
    may produce a Dict<int, U> instantiation never seen before). Each
    pass uses the *_inst_count dictionaries to detect whether the
    instantiation set grew; if it did, run again. Without fixpoint
    iteration, late-discovered instantiations would survive into Phase 5
    and trip validate_post_mono.
    """

  invariant "Name Mangling":
    procedural
    """
    type_to_mangle converts an LType to a C-compatible name fragment:
    primitives → their name (i32, string, bool), classes → "C"+name,
    structs → "S"+name, slices → "slice_"+elem_mangle, maps →
    "map_"+key_mangle+"_"+val_mangle, optionals → "opt_"+inner_mangle.
    type_key joins per-arg mangles with commas to form a stable key for
    the instantiation dictionaries. mangle_name joins base + mangled args
    with underscores to form the final specialized symbol
    (Dict<string,i32> → Dict_string_i32). This scheme MUST stay
    deterministic and injective: two distinct type-arg tuples must produce
    distinct names, otherwise filter_funcs/filter_classes will collapse
    specializations and the program will miscompile.
    """

  invariant "Impl Method Renames":
    procedural
    """
    impl_method_renames uses @-delimited keys of the form
    "IfaceName@TypeArgs@Method" to map an interface-method call site to
    the concrete implementing method. rewrite_impl_renames expands each
    such entry to cover every monomorphized variant of the implementing
    type BEFORE the program walk begins, so subsequent rewrites see a
    flat dictionary keyed by concrete type. rewrite_impl_method_calls
    then uses each function's relational constraints (the LIR's record
    of "this TypeVar implements IfaceName") to pick the right entry and
    apply it to interface-dispatched method calls inside the function.
    """

  invariant "Per-Function ClassRenameMap":
    procedural
    """
    classRenames is a single global Dict that maps generic class names to
    one specialized name — necessarily last-writer-wins when a generic
    class is instantiated at multiple type-arg tuples. Per-function
    correctness instead relies on current_class_rename_map, built by
    build_class_rename_map from the function's specialization substitution.
    resolve_class_names installs that map for each specialized function
    before walking its body, so LTyClass / alloc / cast references inside
    the function resolve to THIS specialization rather than whichever one
    happened to be written into the global map last.
    """

